metadata.name: CR Art Sessions //1 #99
metadata.description:
In Argentina there is a very young and talented music producer called BIZARRAP.

He is very famous for the BZRP Music Sessions, which are tracks in collaboration with international artists that Bizarrap produces in his studio, which also serves as a recording studio for the official video clip of the track.

In these sessions the artists have the freedom to express themselves in ways that perhaps the industry doesn't allow them because they have an image to sell, or the freedom to deliver whatever they want.

For example, in the Music Session with Nicky Jam, the Puerto Rican artist sings rap in Spanish, English and reggaeton, all in the same song.

Inspired by this concept I decided to launch my CR Art Sessions format. The idea is to take previous works and reconvert them or give me the freedom to play with the algorithms and explore new options and parameters to reach their limits or to obtain something different but with the same essence.

The CR Art Sessions //1 is based on my first fx(hash) project called Geoetris. 

The same algorithm was slightly modified to produce 3 different types of art that the user will be able to visualize. 
1. The first type is an extreme version of the Geoetris project, where the parameters were modified to have blend between the pieces and generate many more elements on screen. 
2. The second is a composition of circles and squares, where there is a very simple rule that can only sometimes be broken and that is that the rectangles start in the middle of the circle. 
3. The third is a version where the larger geometric shapes are not filled and only their silhouette is marked.

-----

Reserves: All 'Geoetris' owners and 40-40 slots for 'Yo automata' and 'Isomeric Doppelgangers' owners

-----

Royalties: 50% to minter

-----

Controls:

Explore each art variant with the '1', '2', '3' keys

The 'e' key exports the current canvas

The 's' key exports the image in 3200x4000 px resolution

-----

Artwork by @cristianrohr (2022)

Made with P5js and <3.

metadata.name: Bacteria Scanner #3
metadata.description: A new bacteria scanning device has arrived.â€˜Scanner technologies rely upon specific types of chemical compounds called receptors that bind to biological material including microbes, viruses and nucleic acids found within cells. With the arrival of antibiotic resistance strains, scientists must start thinking of alternatives to combat infectious diseases.One solution could lie in identifying and treating bacterial infections earlier before drug resistant organisms develop, for instance using technology to detect new species of microorganisms. New technologies always bring some problems along with benefits.Although bacterial diseases continue to pose significant threats to humans, research shows that we are beginning to see improvements in ways to combat them.As soon as a disease becomes resistant to antibiotics, the situation worsens again.The recent invention of DNA scanners solves this issue and allows scientists to identify and find out about specific bacterium infections before symptoms arise, thus providing a solution with Hydra.

metadata.name: Bored Computer Screen #296
metadata.description:
"Bored Computer Screen" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022


Bored Computer Screen (BCS) is a direct descendant of SpecterðŸ‘»pixelâ¬›latteâ˜•, where the central idea is agent and displacement. In BCS, there are agentsâ€”the small moving circlesâ€”that get their colors ripped away by the surrounding pixels. Though they occur on the same screen space, they are separated in their own cells, a simultaneous multiverse of sorts. In some iterations, a very clear voronoi pattern will appear. I didn't consciously strive for this look. It's what naturally happens, when you try to divide space, so that the borders occur exactly in between the closest neighbor. When I first saw this pattern emerge, I wanted to see how far I could get the distinct cells to influence each other. The idea that the same algorithmic processes can happen many times but still separately in a single piece has always interested me (and explored in the Infinite Browse series). BCS is an extension of that, albeit a little more chaotic.

Note:
- Best experience on browsers and devices with support for WebGL2 

Made by Sam Tsao (@sam___tsao) with P5, P5Fbo and perlinjs.

metadata.name: Relic #8
metadata.description: This is my 3rd project on fxhash! I was inspired by some black and white circle art and tried to mimic the techniques. From there, my own taste and creativity took over. This is the result. There are 3 shapes - circle, square, and triangle, and 3 colors - pink, blue, and gold. Each work can have multiple layers or "rings" going outwards. Each layer is subdivided randomly and can have pieces missing. This produces some interesting results! Often surprising and sometimes delightful. They look like ancient "relics" to me, so hence the name :) Please enjoy.

metadata.name: Dreamcatcher Forest #308
metadata.description:
"Dreamcatcher Forest" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022. The illustration in this work draws inspiration from Native American dreamcatchers, a protective talisman crafted from beautifully intricate patterns of woven thread, built from natural materials & colorful beads.

Dreamcatchers are used to protect dreamers while they sleep. Good dreams are able to slip through the web to meet the sleeper beneath, while bad dreams are trapped and prevented.

- Use the "S" key to save a PNG image.
- Use the "P" key to export a print-quality image.

metadata.name: Mythic Latent Glitches  #198
metadata.description:
What is even real and what is artificial?

In the contemporary light, the division between real and artificial loses weight as the concepts become more and more intertwined. In this work, the artist combines the human and generative inputs, in a counterintuitive manner, by allowing AI to design the organic elements and using the human hand to incorporate artificial glitches. What seemingly emerges as natural forms, was imagined solely by GAN, seeing the world through the limited examples through the photographerâ€™s lenses. Artistâ€™s role is also reversed, as their goal is to design the visual destruction process of the organic forms. Glitch is a malfunction of perception, it symbolizes the confusion caused by not being able to comprehend. 

The human fascination with metaphysical forces spans many centuries. While Pagan mythology created gods living in deep forests and under-explored territories, nowadays we approach technology with somewhat similar awe, fascination, and fear. 

The project has been developed in multiple stages. It started with an inspiration by the Lithuanian landscape and research of the ancient myths and legends. The photography aimed at capturing the mysterious, spanning months and years of different experiences. A custom pre-trained artistâ€™s GAN model was then trained on a collection of several hundred photographs in high resolution. Selected outputs were curated by artist and included as a starting canvas for the next stage. Then, a set of stochastic manipulations were programmed to create alternative narratives through the visual destruction. Fog turns into smoke into burning radioactive forest in an unpredictable manner, guided by the random variables, their boundaries crafted by artist.  

Read more on the project website:
ivonatau.com/mythic-latent-glitches

- Use the "A" key to animate (if "Animated" feature is present).
- Press any key to stop the animation.
- Use the "S" key to export an image.

metadata.name: Dencity #731
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with â¤ï¸, code and p5js.
